body:
Hi @NastasiaSaby , could you include a directory view of the artifact viewer in the UI (expanded) to show the structure of the run? 
I'm not able to reproduce this and am wondering if some additional files got written into the ALS model directory (which would throw an error like this). 

Also, for what it's worth, here's likely an easier way of retrieving an artifact through the APIs on Databricks:

```python

experiment_id = mlflow.get_experiment_by_name("/Users/nastasia/ALS_experiment").experiment_id
run_info = mlflow.search_runs(experiment_id, order_by=["start_time DESC"]).loc[0]
artifact_uri = f"{run_info["artifact_uri"]}/als_exp"
```
(you don't need to instantiate and use the client from within Databricks :)  )

@NastasiaSaby 
I think we tracked down the culprit. There was a pathing regression that was introduced in 1.28 for SparkML models. It was fixed with #6683. 
Could you try to utilize MLflow 1.29.0 release and let me know if that solves the problem?
Sorry for the inconvenience!
@BenWilson2 , unfortunately, we still have the problem. I'm gonna try to find a way to make it more reproductible.

<!-- assign-maintainer -->
@BenWilson2 @dbczumar @harupy @WeichenXu123 Please assign a maintainer and start triaging this issue.

@BenWilson2 I'm coming back with more info. I've succeeded to reproduce it on the community Databricks edition. You'll find  the notebook and the Python file to reproduce the problem here: https://github.com/NastasiaSaby/bug_mlflow
You can directly import them.
Cluster : 11.2 ML Databricks

This notebook shows that the problem is still on the 1.29 version: https://github.com/NastasiaSaby/bug_mlflow/blob/main/Test_29.ipynb

And here is the cluster configuration:

`{
    "num_workers": 0,
    "cluster_name": "mlflow",
    "spark_version": "11.2.x-cpu-ml-scala2.12",
    "spark_conf": {

        "spark.databricks.delta.preview.enabled": "true"
    },

    "autotermination_minutes": 120,
    "enable_elastic_disk": false,
    "cluster_source": "UI",

}`

@NastasiaSaby Thank you for the thorough investigation. We'll take a look at how ALS behaves within the "spark" flavor for MLflow and determine if we need to add special handling to support this due to the different behavior of how ALS stores its serialized model (as it is storing actual sets of tables). 
This might take some time due to other pending work, so please bear with us.
@BenWilson2 , no problem. For the moment, we'll stick to 1.27.
